---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="What Learn It Anyway is, why it exists, and what it believes."
>
  <header class="mb-10 pb-8 border-b border-white/[0.06]">
    <p class="text-[10px] tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-cyan-400/60 mb-4 font-mono-brand">About</p>
    <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold text-white leading-tight mb-4">
      Most of us learn things only when life demands them.
    </h1>
    <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm font-mono-brand">Navneet R. Mahajan — learning in public.</p>
  </header>

  <div class="max-w-2xl text-slate-400 text-base leading-loose space-y-5">

    <!-- Opening -->
    <p>
      A new project arrives, and suddenly we need to understand Docker. A system breaks, and we rush to
      learn databases. AI becomes impossible to ignore, and we spend weekends watching videos trying to
      catch up. Learning becomes reactive. Necessary. Urgent.
    </p>
    <p>For a long time, I learned that way too.</p>
    <p>
      But I remember listening to senior engineers talk about servers, databases, caching, and system
      design — and realizing how little I understood. I didn't need any of it at the time. I was just
      curious and wanted to understand what everyone was talking about.
    </p>
    <p>That curiosity never really went away.</p>
    <p>
      I consumed endlessly — reels, shorts, random videos, blogs, YouTube tutorials, articles, and tweets.
      Much of it was just mindless scrolling disguised as productivity. There was always another playlist
      to save, another tab to open, another idea I promised myself I would learn someday. I kept assuming
      I would get to it later.
    </p>
    <p>
      Eventually, I realized that if I was going to spend time consuming content anyway, I could spend it
      learning something useful and documenting it. Understanding doesn't appear when we need it. It
      compounds long before that.
    </p>
    <p>That simple thought became <strong class="text-white">Learn It Anyway</strong>.</p>

    <div class="space-y-1.5 text-slate-500 text-sm pl-1 border-l border-white/[0.08]">
      <p>Not as a course.</p>
      <p>Not as a portfolio.</p>
      <p>Not as a personal brand trying to sound like an authority.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-300 pt-1">Just a notebook on the internet.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-300">A place to document curiosity in public.</p>
    </div>

    <p>
      Most of the notes here revolve around software architecture, backend engineering, databases, AI,
      DevOps, and engineering decisions. Sometimes they drift into books, mental models, or ideas that
      seem too interesting not to write down.
    </p>
    <div class="text-sm space-y-1">
      <p class="text-slate-500">The topics change.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-300">Curiosity doesn't.</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- Learn Before You Need It -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-white font-bold text-lg font-mono-brand">Learn Before You Need It</h2>
      <p>That's the philosophy behind everything here.</p>
      <p>
        Because understanding something before necessity arrives changes the way you think. It creates
        intuition. It makes decisions easier. It makes adapting easier.
      </p>
      <p>Technology changes constantly. Frameworks rise and disappear. Trends come and go.</p>
      <p>But understanding how things work keeps paying dividends.</p>
      <div class="border-l-2 border-cyan-400 pl-4 py-1 space-y-1">
        <p class="text-slate-300">Learning isn't an expense.</p>
        <p class="text-cyan-400 font-mono-brand text-sm tracking-wide">It's compound interest.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- Curiosity Is an Advantage -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-white font-bold text-lg font-mono-brand">Curiosity Is an Advantage</h2>
      <p>
        Darwin's idea of "survival of the fittest" is often misunderstood. The winners aren't always
        the strongest or the smartest.
      </p>
      <p>They are the ones that adapt.</p>
      <p>And in technology, adaptability comes from curiosity.</p>

      <div class="space-y-2 pt-1">
        {[
          { text: 'Curious people keep asking questions.', accent: false },
          { text: 'Curious people keep learning.',         accent: false },
          { text: 'Curious people adapt.',                 accent: false },
          { text: 'Curious people survive.',               accent: true  },
        ].map(({ text, accent }) => (
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-sm font-mono-brand">
            <span class="text-cyan-400/40">›</span>
            <span class={accent ? 'text-cyan-400' : 'text-slate-300'}>{text}</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <p>That matters even more now.</p>
      <p>
        As AI becomes increasingly capable, writing code is becoming easier. But software engineering
        has never been just about typing code.
      </p>
      <p class="text-white font-medium">Someone still has to decide.</p>

      <!-- Trade-off questions -->
      <div class="border border-white/[0.08] bg-white/[0.02] px-5 py-4 font-mono-brand text-sm space-y-2">
        {[
          'Monolith or microservices?',
          'PostgreSQL or MongoDB?',
          'Redis or no Redis?',
          'Optimize now or later?',
          'Build it or buy it?',
        ].map((q) => (
          <p class="text-slate-400"><span class="text-cyan-400/50 mr-2">_</span>{q}</p>
        ))}
      </div>

      <p>Trade-offs don't disappear. If anything, they become more important.</p>
      <p>Good decisions require understanding.</p>

      <div class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-slate-500 pl-1 border-l border-white/[0.08]">
        <p>Not memorization.</p>
        <p>Not blindly following trends.</p>
        <p class="text-slate-300">Understanding concepts.</p>
        <p class="text-slate-300">Building intuition.</p>
        <p class="text-slate-300">Thinking in trade-offs.</p>
      </div>

      <p>That's what I'm trying to learn.</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- From Consuming to Creating -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-white font-bold text-lg font-mono-brand">From Consuming to Creating</h2>
      <p>For years, I consumed far more than I created.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">Books. Videos. Podcasts. Courses. Endless information.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">And plenty of reels, shorts, and hours lost to mindless scrolling.</p>
      <p>Eventually, consuming stopped being enough.</p>
      <div class="space-y-1.5 text-sm font-mono-brand text-slate-400">
        <p>Writing became a way to understand.</p>
        <p>Explaining became a way to think.</p>
        <p>Sharing became a way to learn.</p>
      </div>
      <p>This website is an attempt to create more than I consume.</p>
      <div class="space-y-1 text-sm">
        <p class="text-slate-500">Less scrolling.</p>
        <p class="text-slate-300">More making.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- Where the name came from -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <p>So I decided to learn. One rabbit hole at a time.</p>
      <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">
        No mentor to guide me through it. No team to bounce decisions off. No production system to
        test ideas against. Just curiosity and the internet.
      </p>
      <p>And I kept running into reasons not to bother.</p>
      <div class="space-y-1 text-slate-500 text-sm pl-1 border-l border-white/[0.08]">
        <p>I can't implement this at scale right now.</p>
        <p>I don't have the context a senior engineer has.</p>
        <p>What if I get it wrong?</p>
      </div>
      <p>But I kept going anyway.</p>
      <div class="space-y-2 pt-1 text-sm font-mono-brand">
        <p class="text-slate-400">Even without a mentor — <span class="text-white">I'll learn it anyway.</span></p>
        <p class="text-slate-400">Even without a way to implement it right now — <span class="text-white">I'll learn it anyway.</span></p>
        <p class="text-slate-400">Even if I end up getting half of it wrong — <span class="text-white">I'll learn it anyway.</span></p>
      </div>
      <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm">That's where the name came from.</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- Learning in Public -->
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-white font-bold text-lg font-mono-brand">Learning in Public</h2>
      <p>Nothing here is presented as absolute truth.</p>
      <div class="space-y-1 text-slate-500 text-sm">
        <p>Some ideas will change.</p>
        <p>Some opinions will be wrong.</p>
        <p>Some notes will age badly.</p>
      </div>
      <p>That's fine.</p>
      <p>Knowledge evolves, and hopefully so will I.</p>
      <p>
        If you know something I don't, corrections are welcome.<br/>
        If you're learning too, you're welcome to learn alongside me.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because the goal isn't to teach from a pedestal. The goal is simply to understand how things
        work — and leave behind notes for whoever might find them useful.
      </p>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-white/[0.06] !my-10" />

    <!-- Closing manifesto -->
    <div class="border border-white/[0.08] bg-white/[0.02] p-6 sm:p-8">
      <p class="text-white font-semibold mb-5">
        <span class="text-cyan-400">Learn It Anyway</span> is a curious engineer's notebook on the internet.
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-400 font-mono-brand">
        <p>Curiosity over credentials.</p>
        <p>Understanding over memorization.</p>
        <p>Adaptability over certainty.</p>
        <p>Creation over consumption.</p>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-6 text-slate-500 text-sm">
        And the belief that some things are worth learning long before life asks for them.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</Layout>
